04562nam a22006735i 9780824845735DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t19991999hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248457357 a10.1515/97808248457352doi  a(DE-B1597)484362  a(OCoLC)1013940940  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aU55.S386b.R464 1999 7aBIO0080002bisacsh04a355.00922211 aGoro, Shiba, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRemembering Aizu :bThe Testament of Shiba Goro /cShiba Goro; ed. by Ishimitsu Mahita. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[1999] 4c©1999  a1 online resource (168 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tRemembering Aizu. The Testament of Shiba Gorō -- tPreface -- tChildhood -- tBeginning of the Tragedy -- tReaction in Aizu -- tA Fight to the Death -- tA Sea of Fire -- tA Night of Despair -- tLast Days of the Bakufu -- tA Time of Trial for the Family -- tDetention Camp in Edo -- tJourney to Hell -- tThe Fight against Famine -- tA Ray of Hope in the Wilderness -- tTokyo: The Old and the New -- tThe Happiest Day of My Life -- tMilitary School -- tThe Satsuma Rebellion -- tEnd of the Satsuma Rebellion -- tTranslator’s Afterword -- tNotes -- tBibliography0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Meiji Restoration of 1868 is most often seen as a glorious event marking the overthrow of Tokugawa feudalism and the beginning of Japan's modern transformation. Yet it had its dark side. The Aizu domain in northeastern Japan had staunchly supported the old regime. For this it was attacked by the new government's forces from Choshu and Satsuma in the autumn of 1868. Its castle town was burned to the ground, and during a month-long siege, whole families perished. After defeat, the domain was abolished and its samurai population exiled to barren terrain in the far north.Shiba Goro was born into an Aizu samurai family in 1859. He was just ten years old at the time of the attack, which claimed most of his family. In the cruel world of exile, he lived with his father on the edge of starvation, struggling to survive. Eventually making his way to Tokyo, he became a servant, and though born in an enemy domain, gained entrance to a military school of the new regime. Shiba's abilities were recognized, and he rose through the officer ranks to become a full general - a singular distinction for an Aizu samurai in an army dominated by former samurai of the Choshu domain.Remembering Aizu tells of Shiba's earlier years. It is an extraordinary story that provides insights and material for a social history of the Restoration and its aftermath. But above all, it is a vividly rendered personal account of courage and determination, loss and remembrance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aGeneralszJapanvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Military.2bisacsh1 aCraig, Teruko.1 aMahita, Ishimitsu, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311056415040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082484573540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824845735423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824845735/original  a978-3-11-056415-0  University of Hawaii Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK